    Tones ( Note that when combining with nasals, the ς of the nasal finals wll be omitted ):
    - Latin:
        dark flat:  pa
        light flat: past ( at the end of a word )
                    pas ( before a vowel)
                    paso ( before a consonant )
        rising:     pass ( doubling the next consonant, when followed by a vowel use -ss )
                    pat ( at the end of a word )
        departing:  pav ( before a vowel )
                    pavo ( before a consonant or at the end of a word )
        light:      pas ( at the end of a word )
    - Greek:
        dark flat:  πα
                    παλον ( before a vowel )
                    παλετο ( at the end of a word )
        light flat: πασαι ( at the end of a word )
                    πασ ( before a vowel)
                    πασο ( before a consonant )
        rising:     paσσ ( doubling the next consonant except for φ, θ, χ, ψ, ζ, and ξ, which will become φθ, σθ, χθ, πτ, στ, and κτ; when followed by a vowel use -σσ )
                    paτος ( at the end of a word )
        departing:  paξ ( before a vowel or at the end of a word )
                    paξo ( before a consonant )
        light:      paς ( at the end of a word )

Example:
    Giammout pruevobiano creuo criego "ciggo", liust laullaus biavono priavonocito crieno laest, gaucriego creuodauvo,
    "laulliust, laulliust, criestoliavogo davo roust niust: triegevo laut mouppreou, bouvo taestoteost!"
    Creuo hoastono, cuevo goupprues craebagopris, liagossianno priesto crievo, hicriego bouvut.
    Pruovogo restono chiano chaesto phapriego, cheovolaest hichiaggo, criavogo criavogo chiavo chiavo deo hicisto
    chacha davochiovo cillaes. 